                  <persName xml:lang="gez" xml:id="n1" type="birth">በትረ፡ ጌላ፡ ማርያም፡</persName>
               <persName xml:lang="gez" corresp="#n1" type="normalized">Batra Gelā Māryām</persName>
          
                  <persName>
                  <roleName type="title">ʾabbā </roleName>
               </persName>
                  <nationality type="Ethiopia"/>
                  <faith type="EOTC"/>
                  <occupation type="ecclesiastic">saint</occupation>
                <floruit> He was a medieval saint refered as a son of the prince. As a child he was imprisoned and tortured together with his brothers on the order of his own father. 
                     The account resembles  stories that are told in the royal Ethiopian chronicles, where it said that 
                     <roleName type="title">ʾaṣe</roleName>
                  <persName ref="PRS10626ZaraY">Zarʾa Yāʿqob</persName> acted resolutely against his sons after charges were made 
                     against them that they were practicing pagan rites. Thus, <persName ref="PRS2536BatraGe">Batra Gelā Māryām</persName> could possibly identified with   
                   <roleName type="title">ʾaṣe</roleName>
                  <persName ref="PRS2334BaedaM">Baʾǝda Māryām I</persName>, son and successor of   
                     <roleName type="title">ʾaṣe</roleName>
                  <persName ref="PRS10626ZaraY">Zarʾa Yāʿqob</persName>. 
                     A fragment of his Acts, found in the <title ref="LIT2384Taamme">Taʾammǝra Māryām</title>
               </floruit>
                 
               </person>
